1. The Core Libraries
    PyQt6.QtWidgets
        Definition: The primary toolkit containing the physical,
                    interactive building blocks for a desktop application.

        Usage: Used to summon every visible element on the screen, including the main window (QMainWindow),
               buttons (QPushButton), typing boxes (QLineEdit), dropdown menus (QComboBox), and pop-up alerts (QMessageBox).

    PyQt6.QtCore
        Definition: The engine that handles non-visual, background logic and constants.

        Usage: Used specifically for the Qt object, which provides absolute rules, such as
                Qt.MatchFlag.MatchFixedString, to ensure the search function looks for exact word
                matches rather than partial guesses.

    PyQt6.QtGui
        Definition: The library that handles 2D graphics and visual styling elements.

        Usage: Used to import QIcon (to put small pictures on buttons) and QAction
                (to create clickable items inside the top menu bar).

    sqlite3
        Definition: The built-in Python database engine.

        Usage: Used to translate the Python script's intent into raw SQL queries,
                allowing the application to permanently read, write, and delete records in the local database.db file.

    sys
        Definition: A system-level library that interacts directly with the computer's operating system.

        Usage: Used strictly to pass computer system arguments to the app upon launch
                (sys.argv) and to cleanly terminate the program when the window is closed (sys.exit()).

2. The Custom Classes and Methods

    Class: DatabaseConnection
        Definition: A custom blueprint strictly dedicated to managing the
                    pathway between the Python app and the SQL database.

        Method: __init__: Sets the default target file to database.db.

        Method: connect: Physically opens and returns the active pipeline to the database so other classes can
                         send data through it.

    Class: MainWindow (Inherits from QMainWindow)
        Definition: The primary, persistent desktop window that holds the main data table and toolbars.

        Method: __init__: The assembly line. It builds the 800x600 window, constructs the top menu bars,
                            sets up the table columns (Id, Name, Course, Mobile), and wires the menu buttons
                            to their respective functions.

        Method: load_data: The retrieval engine. It queries the database for every existing student
                            record and uses a loop to inject that data into the visual table, row by row.

        Method: cell_clicked: A dynamic trigger. When a mouse clicks a specific row in the table,
                                this method spawns the "Edit Record" and "Delete Record" buttons at the bottom of the screen.

        Methods: insert, search, edit, delete, about: These are simple trigger switches.
                 Their only job is to summon the corresponding pop-up dialog box when a button is pressed.

    Class: AboutDialog (Inherits from QMessageBox)
        Definition: A simple, static notification window.

        Method: __init__: Hardcodes the text "This app is created to store student's information..."
                            and displays it on the screen.

    Class: InsertDialog (Inherits from QDialog)
        Definition: A pop-up form containing blank fields to collect new student data.

        Method: __init__: Draws the blank text boxes, the dropdown menu for courses, and the "Submit" button.

        Method: add_student: Extracts the typed text from the boxes, connects to the database,
                executes an INSERT INTO SQL command to save the new row, closes the connection,
                and commands the main window to refresh the table.

    Class: EditDialog (Inherits from QDialog)
        Definition: A pop-up form designed to modify existing records.

        Method: __init__: Identifies exactly which row was clicked in the main table,
                            extracts that specific data, and pre-fills the text boxes so they can be modified.

        Method: update_student: Executes an UPDATE SQL command, overwriting the old database
                                record with whatever new text was typed into the boxes.

    Class: DeleteDialog (Inherits from QDialog)
        Definition: A safety checkpoint pop-up asking for confirmation before data destruction.

        Method: __init__: Generates a window asking "Are you sure you want to delete?" with Yes/No buttons.

        Method: delete_student: If "Yes" is clicked, it identifies the hidden ID of the selected student,
                                 executes a DELETE from students WHERE id = ? SQL command, wipes the record,
                                  and flashes a "Success" message.

    Class: SearchDialog (Inherits from QDialog)
        Definition: A locator pop-up used to find specific students.

        Method: __init__: Generates a single search bar and a "Search" button.

        Method: search: Takes the typed name, queries the database, and if a match is found,
                        visually highlights the correct row on the main desktop window behind the pop-up.